      <h2 style="font-family: Georgia, serif; font-size: clamp(22px, 3vw, 30px); font-weight: 700; color: #1C1C1E; line-height: 1.25; margin: 0 0 12px 0;">What defines daily life in Knutsford?</h2>
      <p style="font-family: Inter, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.75; color: #444444; margin: 0 0 16px 0;">Knutsford centres on King Street - a tree-lined high street where Belle Epoque, The Courthouse restaurant, and King Street Townhouse occupy Georgian and Victorian buildings alongside independent boutiques and wine merchants. Princess Street runs parallel, hosting the monthly Makers Market and pubs including The Lord Eldon and The Freemasons Arms. Curzon Knutsford operates a two-screen independent cinema within the town centre.</p>
      <p style="font-family: Inter, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.75; color: #444444; margin: 0 0 16px 0;">Waitrose and Booths anchor the weekly shop - Booths being a premium Northern grocer with no equivalent south of Lancaster (distinct from Booths Park, the business campus on Toft Road). The compact, walkable core distinguishes Knutsford from other Golden Triangle towns where the retail and dining offer is less concentrated in a single pedestrian street.</p>

      <h3 style="font-family: Georgia, serif; font-size: 20px; font-weight: 700; color: #1C1C1E; margin: 32px 0 12px 0;">How close is Tatton Park to Knutsford town centre?</h3>
      <p style="font-family: Inter, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.75; color: #444444; margin: 0 0 16px 0;">Knutsford borders Tatton Park's 1,000-acre estate directly, with the main entrance accessible from the town centre. The park draws 500,000+ visitors annually for its Regency mansion, Japanese garden, deer park, farm, and 100+ annual events including RHS Flower Show Tatton Park (National Trust, 2025). The Tatton Park Knutsford gate on Mereheath Lane opens onto dog-walking, running, and cycling trails directly accessible from the town centre on foot.</p>
      <p style="font-family: Inter, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.75; color: #444444; margin: 0 0 16px 0;">Beyond Tatton Park, Knutsford connects to several natural areas within a short distance. Knutsford Heath covers 36 acres of ancient common land with broadleaved woodland, scrub, and heathland habitats (Cheshire Wildlife Trust). The Moor - 5.5 acres within a conservation area, opened 1907 - extends Knutsford's green space to within 15 minutes' walk of over 5,500 households (Cheshire East Council). Pickmere Lake sits 4 miles north for quieter walking and fishing. The Peak District National Park boundary lies 30 minutes east via the A537 Macclesfield road.</p>

      <h3 style="font-family: Georgia, serif; font-size: 20px; font-weight: 700; color: #1C1C1E; margin: 32px 0 12px 0;">What is the Cranford connection to Knutsford?</h3>
      <p style="font-family: Inter, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.75; color: #444444; margin: 0;">Knutsford inspired Elizabeth Gaskell's 1851 novel Cranford - she was raised in the town from the age of 13 months and based the story on its social customs and buildings. A Cranford Trail walking route follows her connection. The Royal May Day festival - running continuously since 1864 - features a procession of approximately 600 children, crowning of a May Queen, and the unique local tradition of sanding the streets with coloured sand patterns.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Employment -->
  <section style="padding: clamp(32px, 5vw, 56px) 24px;">
